---

<Layout title="Logic Ch.6 — Predicate Logic" favicon="🔑">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/logic/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to logic</a>

    <h1>Predicate Logic</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Craig DeLancey &middot; A Concise Introduction to Logic, Ch. 6 &middot; <a href="https://milneopentextbooks.org/a-concise-introduction-to-logic/">CC BY-SA 4.0</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><strong>Predicate logic</strong> extends propositional logic with predicates (properties of objects), quantifiers (&forall; "for all", &exist; "there exists"), and variables. It can express statements about individuals in a domain that propositional logic cannot.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Domain of discourse with predicate highlighted -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 320 180" class="w-full max-w-sm" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Domain oval -->
        <ellipse cx="160" cy="90" rx="140" ry="70" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.3"/>
        <text x="160" y="170" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.35">Domain D</text>
        <!-- Elements NOT satisfying P -->
        <circle cx="70" cy="80" r="12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.3"/>
        <text x="70" y="84" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">c</text>
        <circle cx="120" cy="110" r="12" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.3"/>
        <text x="120" y="114" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">d</text>
